Before we leave the Great Bridge let us consider for a moment the very interesting question of the number of houses which the town contained in the thirteenth' century; and especially the number to be assigned to the district which we have just left, and which in the Memoranda (p. 282) is styled “Beyond Bridge (Ultra pontemt”

Domesday Book tells us that Grentebrige contained 400 houses divided into ten wards; that of those 400 houses 27 had been destroyed to make room for the castle; and that two oi the ten wards had been thrown together. lt has usually been the custom to assume that all these houses and wards were transpontine; but this view has been contested by Professor Maitland¹‚ who has made a careful analysis of the Cambridge of the Hundred Rolls, and shews thatin 1279 the whole town had only about 550 houses of which not more than 72 were allotted to the three transpontine parishes ol S. Giles, S. Peter, and All Saints. He states his view in the following brilliant passage:
